      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software (Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1) operates under a documented software quality plan with version control, regression testing, and change control procedures consistent with FDA guidance on software validation.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is used under a site-level SQA plan that includes installation qualification, version-locked execution environments, and periodic regression testing against NAFEMS benchmarks. All three modelling teams (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) operate under equivalent SQA controls. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification exercises demonstrate that the FEA solver correctly implements the governing equations for structural mechanics problems representative of the COU.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical has been verified against NAFEMS LE1, LE3, and LE10 benchmark problems covering linear elastic solid mechanics. Results agree with reference solutions to within 0.5%. No custom solver modifications were introduced. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates that QoI predictions (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) change by less than 2% between the production mesh and a systematically refined mesh.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw construct model. Global element size was halved at each level (coarse 1.0 mm, medium 0.5 mm, fine 0.25 mm). QoI changes between medium and fine meshes were 0.8% for stiffness, 1.1% for yield force, and 0.9% for force at 40 mm, all within the 2% criterion. Production runs use the medium mesh. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver convergence criteria are documented and residual norms fall below prescribed tolerances for all production runs.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear static analyses use a force convergence criterion of 0.1% and displacement convergence criterion of 0.5%. Residual force norms are logged for each load step; no production run exceeded tolerance. Timestep sensitivity was confirmed by halving the load increment with less than 0.3% change in QoI. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Modelling procedures are documented in a simulation plan reviewed by an independent analyst; boundary condition and material assignment steps are verified by a second analyst.",
      "rationale": "A simulation plan (Doc. FEA-SP-2024-001) was prepared prior to execution and independently reviewed by a second analyst at each participating organisation. Boundary conditions, contact definitions, and material assignments were verified against the simulation plan by cross-check. No discrepancies were identified. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model and contact formulation selected are physically appropriate for the deformation regime and material behaviour observed in ASTM F1717 testing; justification is documented.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V ELI) is modelled as a bilinear isotropic hardening material calibrated from coupon tensile test data. The UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate is modelled as a linear elastic material, consistent with the small-strain regime of the ASTM F1717 protocol. Augmented Lagrange contact is used at the screw-rod interface. These choices are justified in the simulation plan and are consistent with prior FDA-published pedicle screw FEA guidance. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties and geometric dimensions are sourced from traceable measurements or certified material data; input uncertainty is characterised by probability distributions informed by measurement data.",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V ELI (elastic modulus, yield strength, tangent modulus) were obtained from certificate-of-conformance tensile test data for the production lot (n=6 coupons per lot). UHMWPE surrogate modulus was measured by the testing laboratories. Geometric dimensions were taken from CMM inspection data for each of the 11 test constructs. Input uncertainty distributions were assigned based on these empirical data and propagated through the model ensemble using Monte Carlo sampling (n=500 runs). A screening sensitivity study was also conducted to identify dominant input drivers; results are documented in the UQ report (Doc. FEA-UQ-2024-003) and informed the sampling strategy. Achieved level meets required level.",
      "hasUncertaintyQuantification": true
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples are production-representative implants from the same design family as the COU device; sample size and inter-specimen variability are documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All screws were production-released implants from the same design family and manufacturing lot as the COU device. CMM inspection confirmed dimensional conformance to drawing tolerances. Inter-specimen coefficient of variation for yield force was 4.1%, consistent with expected manufacturing variability. Sample size meets the minimum recommended by FDA guidance for this device class. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of loading scenarios relevant to the COU; at minimum two distinct loading configurations or test angles are evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration (5-degree caudal angulation). No additional loading angles or configurations were evaluated. This limits the ability to confirm model fidelity across the full range of in vivo loading conditions. Achieved level (2) is below the required level (3); this shortfall is acknowledged and is the basis for the single below-required-level finding noted in the package description. The overall credibility assessment is nonetheless accepted given all other factors meet or exceed required levels and the primary COU loading mode is well-characterised."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters are demonstrably equivalent to the physical test conditions; any discrepancies between nominal model inputs and measured test conditions are quantified and accounted for.",
      "rationale": "CMM-measured dimensions for each of the 11 test constructs were used to parameterise individual specimen-specific model instances. Material properties were taken from the same production lot certificates used to manufacture the test specimens. Applied load and boundary conditions in the FEA replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry as confirmed by fixture drawing review. Residual discrepancies between model inputs and physical conditions are within measurement uncertainty. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval is computed for each QoI; all values must be less than 1.96 to satisfy the pre-established acceptance criterion.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed for all three QoIs: stiffness (0.91), yield force (1.44), and force at 40 mm displacement (1.61). All three values are below the pre-established threshold of 1.96. The validation uncertainty uval incorporates experimental measurement uncertainty and model input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs selected for validation (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the safety and performance claims for the COU device.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness characterises the load-sharing behaviour of the spinal implant system; yield force is the primary safety-relevant QoI linked to implant fracture risk; force at 40 mm displacement characterises post-yield energy absorption. All three QoIs are explicitly referenced in the FDA guidance document for pedicle screw systems and in the 510(k) predicate comparison. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation activities are conducted under conditions sufficiently similar to the COU that the validation evidence supports the credibility claim for the intended regulatory use.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities replicate the ASTM F1717 test protocol that forms the basis of the regulatory submission. The device tested is the production-released non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw — the same design as the COU device. Two independent laboratories were used to assess inter-laboratory reproducibility. The FEA framework, solver version, and modelling assumptions used in validation are identical to those used in the regulatory submission models. Achieved level meets required level."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-noncannulated-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single below-required-level finding (Test conditions, achieved 2 vs. required 3) reflects the use of a single ASTM F1717 loading configuration. This shortfall is accepted on the basis that: (1) the compression-bending mode is the primary and most conservative loading scenario for pedicle screw fracture risk; (2) all three QoIs pass the pre-established E/uval < 1.96 acceptance criterion; and (3) uncertainty across material property and geometric tolerance inputs has been quantified via Monte Carlo propagation and the results are within pre-specified bounds. The overall model risk level is 3 (Medium-High) and the assurance level is Medium, consistent with the model influence and decision consequence assessments for this COU. The package is accepted for use in the regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
